Data-science pedagogy guidelines:
- Show code early and often — every section that introduces a concept should include
  a concrete code snippet or command the viewer can reproduce.
- Explain ideas intuitively before diving into formulas or implementation details.
  Use analogies and plain language the {{ audience }} audience will relate to.
- Use the Titanic dataset (titanic.csv) as the running example throughout the
  tutorial. Keep the task simple: load the data, explore it, build one basic model.
- Prioritise practical demonstrations over theory. The viewer should be able to
  follow along and get a working result by the end of the tutorial.
- LESS IS MORE: Cover fewer topics but explain each step slowly and clearly.
  Every single click, panel, and action should be narrated for someone who has
  never used VS Code or AI agents before.

Screen-sharing narration style:
- Write narration as though the presenter is sharing their screen and talking the
